alert.title: Update: 30 killed during oil tanker explosion in Lakoja
alert.description: Local media reports that at least 30 people were killed when an oil tanker exploded due to a traffic collision in Lakoja. The incident took place on the A233 at around 09:00 this morning.
alert.notes: Avoid the area of the explosion and allow emergency crews to respond to the incident. Traffic disruption due to closed roads can be expected. For further assistance, training, or advice, please contact the Solace Global Risk operations centre on +44 (0) 1202 795 801 or via sgr@solaceglobal.com.

alert.notes: Solace Global advises travellers to ensure that they are aware of any country-specific travel restrictions that may be in place and have all the relevant documentation available whilst in-country. For further assistance, training, or advice, please contact the Solace Global Risk operations centre on +44 (0) 1202 795 801 or via sgr@solaceglobal.com.

alert.title: Streets flooded in Mumbai after heavy rainfall
alert.description: Video footage released on social media shows flooded streets in parts of Mumbai after heavy rainfall. There is ongoing transport disruption but no casualties have been reported.
alert.notes: Avoid unnecessary travel in the city at this time and anticipate transport disruption for at least the next few hours. Do not attempt to drive through floodwaters due to the risks of submersion and hidden obstacles. For further assistance, training, or advice, please contact the Solace Global Risk operations centre on +44 (0) 1202 795 801 or via sgr@solaceglobal.com.

alert.title: Several large wildfires burning in Cordoba province
alert.description: Media reporting indicates that hundreds of firefighters are currently working to extinguish several large wildfires in Cordoba province. Fires are currently burning in the areas of Villa Carlos Paz, Los Morteritos, Cuchi Corral and Unquillo. As of yet, none of these fires has been effectively brought under control. Further wildfires in the region cannot be ruled out.
alert.notes: Individuals near the affected area are advised to monitor the development of the situation. Wildfires are uncontrolled at present due to high temperatures and strong winds. It is recommended to avoid the area whilst firefighting operations continue. If currently in an evacuation zone, travellers should adhere to local authority instructions and leave as soon as possible by the safest route available. Travellers should anticipate major disruptions to travel, business and essential services in areas affected by bush fires. In addition, travellers should limit outdoor activity and remain hydrated as high temperatures are expected to remain into the near-term. For further assistance, training, or advice, please contact the Solace Global Risk operations centre on +44 (0) 1202 795 801 or via sgr@solaceglobal.com.
